<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>You’re launching a new business or want more customers for your current business. Or perhaps you are a book author who wants more fans to buy your books or eBooks.</p>
<p>You’ve heard about the power of social media for businesses, and you do have a Facebook profile to connect with your friends. But you’re not sure how you can use social media to connect with potential customers or book buyers.</p>
<h3>Blogging can help establish your expertise</h3>
<p>Blogging is social media – you write a blog post and people can comment about the post. Definitely a social experience.</p>
<p>Now for business purposes the topic area of your blog is very important. For example, if you sell handmade bedspreads, it is not a good idea to continually blog about the problems in your hometown with building restrictions unless you can think of a seamless way to include handmade bedspreads in the subject of each blog.</p>
<p>On the other hand, you can stretch your creativity to come up with blog post topics that can include references to your business or book. In fact, thanks to John Locke’s book <a href="http://www.amazon.com/How-Sold-Million-eBooks-Months/dp/1935670913/ref=sr_1_6?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1314575651&amp;sr=1-6">”How I Sold 1 Million eBooks in 5 Months”</a>I came up with a way to write blog posts about current events and include references to my eBook novel <a href="http://www.molliesanders.com">“Lt. Commander Mollie Sanders”</a>.</p>
<p>You definitely want to use blogging to showcase your expertise in connection with your business or book. And when you meet people at in-person networking groups, you can follow up by sending them a link to a specific post that addresses something they mentioned.</p>
<p>Another great reason to blog is that you then have good content to share on other social media sites such as Twitter, Facebook Pages, LinkedIn and now Google+. By using helpful tools such as HootSuite.com, you can send the links to your posts through to several social media sites without having to individually visit each of those sites.</p>
<p>Of course, there’s also the advantage of encouraging others to share your blog posts via sharing applications, as Nicholas does here.</p>
<h3>Join forums such as LinkedIn groups that enable you to showcase your expertise</h3>
<p>Leaving insightful comments on blogs is a good way to get known – especially if you frequently leave comments on the same blog.</p>
<p>But let’s say you frequently leave comments here because you love what Nicholas says about online business as you sell dog beds via a company website. Now while several of the people reading Nicholas’ posts might be potential dog bed buyers, it is a very good idea to interact directly with people who have dogs.</p>
<p>For example, you can go on LinkedIn and do a search in groups for topics related to dogs. Then join the groups with the most members (the search results are returned with the groups in descending member numbers) and start participating by sharing good information on the questions dog owners ask.</p>
<p>You can put your website URL at the end of each comment so that people can learn more about your interest in dogs without you “selling” dog beds in the group. (Tip: You must put http:// in front of any URL you share on LinkedIn in order for it to be a hot link.)</p>
<h3>Participate on sites such as Twitter where you don’t need permission to connect with others</h3>
<p>I personally love Twitter for two main reasons:</p>
<p>1) I really like the limit of 140 characters, which forces people to be succinct instead of rambling on and on and on.</p>
<p>2) I can follow people who might be interested in what I have to offer without, for example, waiting for approval of a Facebook “friend” request or a LinkedIn “connection” request.</p>
<p>And while everyone I’d like to connect with may not follow me back (and many won’t), I have complete freedom to share good content connected to my interests.</p>
<p><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-14289" title="twitter" src="http://www.sitesketch101.com/wp-content/uploads/twitter4.jpg" alt="" width="550" height="100"/></p>
<p><strong>Secret tip:</strong> It doesn’t actually take as much time a day to be active on Twitter as those not yet on Twitter often fear. What it does take is a strategy so that you share worthwhile content in a small amount of time. (For example, you can tweet this post through this site’s tweet button and that’s one Twitter update “done for you.”)</p>
<p>In conclusion, for the above three ways as well as the many other ways that social media can help you get in front of your target audiences, just remember the difference between sharing personal (social) info and private info. Personal might be that you attended a concert; private is a fight you had with your boss. Personal is good; private is not!</p>
